  "prompt": "What is the difference between active voice and passive voice?",
  "response": "The difference between active voice and passive voice lies in the structure of the sentence and the focus on the subject and action.\n\n**Active Voice:**\n- In active voice, the subject of the sentence performs the action. The structure typically follows the pattern: Subject + Verb + Object.\n- Example: \"The cat (subject) chased (verb) the mouse (object).\"\n\n**Passive Voice:**\n- In passive voice, the subject of the sentence receives the action. The structure generally follows the pattern: Subject + Form of \"to be\" + Past Participle + (by + Agent).\n- Example: \"The mouse (subject) was chased (verb) by the cat (agent).\"\n\n**Key Differences:**\n1. **Focus**: Active voice emphasizes the doer of the action, while passive voice emphasizes the action itself and the recipient.\n2. **Clarity**: Active sentences are generally more direct and concise, while passive sentences can sometimes be less clear or more wordy.\n3. **Use Cases**: Passive voice is often used when the doer is unknown, irrelevant, or when the focus is meant to be on the action or recipient.\n\nOverall, the choice between active and passive voice can affect the tone and clarity of writing.",
